Here is the implementation plan, the resource requirements, and the logic fix roadmap.

1. The Strategy: The "Shim" Architecture
To keep the application working without PostgreSQL or Redis, we will create two internal "shims" that mimic their APIs.

Prisma JSON Shim: A service that intercepts prisma.user.findUnique() style calls and routes them to local JSON file operations.
Redis In-Memory Shim: A simple Map-based service that handles token blacklisting and sessions, persisting to a JSON file occasionally so that restarts don't log everyone out.
2. Phase 1: Infrastructure & Data Setup
Objective: Transition from external dependencies to local internal services.

Initialize JSON Storage: Create a backend/data/ directory and seed all 29 tables (models) as JSON arrays.
The Prisma Proxy: Build a jsonDb.js client. This will be the most complex part, as it needs to support filtering (where), inclusion (include), and basic ordering to keep the service files untouched.
Environment Cleanup: Update backend/.env to reference local data paths. We will keep the PORT and JWT_SECRET but discard DATABASE_URL and REDIS_URL.
Railway Config Update: Modify railway.json and railway.toml to remove the Postgres and Redis plugins, reducing your costs and complexity.
3. Phase 2: The "Logic Fix" Roadmap
Objective: Resolve the critical business logic issues identified in the analysis.

The Balance Authority:
Fix: Create a balanceSync utility. Every time a transaction is created or a status changes, this utility will recalculate the "Triple Balance" (balance, availableBalance, pendingBalance).
Loan Fix: Ensure Loan Approvals credit both balance and availableBalance.
Status Normalization:
Fix: Update all services (paymentService, transferService, loanService) to use a global STATUS constant. No more mixed completed vs COMPLETED.
Collision Prevention:
Fix: Update the routingNumber generator to check the JSON database for existence before assigning it to a new user. Use a 12-digit random string for account numbers instead of a sequential one.
Transaction Simulation:
Since JSON files don't support ACID transactions, we will implement a "Write-Ahead" lock. When a file is being updated, other writes will queue for a few milliseconds to prevent data corruption.
4. Phase 3: Frontend "App-Like" Experience
Objective: Implement premium loading states across the dashboard.

Global Loading Skeleton: Create a SkeletonCard and SkeletonList component in frontend/src/components.
Fetching States: Update all 31 dashboard pages to use a unified isLoading pattern.
Transitions: Add CSS transitions (fade-in/blur-up) when data finishes loading to make the UI feel "fluid" rather than "jumpy."
